import ServicePage from "../layouts/ServicePage.astro";
---

<ServicePage
  title="About This Service | Upper Cumberland Well Pump"
  description="What Upper Cumberland Well Pump is, what it does and does not do, and how it connects Upper Cumberland, TN property owners with independent well-service providers."
  path="/about-this-service/"
  h1="About Upper Cumberland Well Pump"
  crumbs={[
    { name: "Home", path: "/" },
    { name: "About This Service", path: "/about-this-service/" },
  ]}
  isService={false}
  defaultService=""
  relatedLinks={[
    { label: "How Referrals Work", href: "/how-referrals-work/" },
    { label: "Referral Disclosure", href: "/referral-disclosure/" },
    { label: "Tennessee Licensing Information", href: "/licensing-information/" },
    { label: "Privacy Policy", href: "/privacy-policy/" },
  ]}
>
  <p>
    Upper Cumberland Well Pump is an independent, online referral resource focused on one thing:
    helping property owners in Cookeville and the wider Upper Cumberland region of Tennessee get
    well-system problems described clearly and routed to independent local providers who can
    actually work on them.
  </p>

  <h2>What This Service Does</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Collects well-pump and water-well service requests through a structured, diagnostic form.
    </li>
    <li>Publishes practical, no-hype information about common private-well problems.</li>
    <li>
      Routes requests toward independent local providers whose coverage and capabilities may fit.
    </li>
    <li>
      Encourages every visitor to verify a provider's current Tennessee license before regulated
      work begins.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What This Service Does Not Do</h2>
  <p>
    Upper Cumberland Well Pump does not directly perform well-pump repair, pump replacement or
    installation, water-well drilling, pressure-tank work, well inspections or water-treatment
    installation unless expressly stated. There are no company trucks, no dispatch center and no
    physical office. The website also does not diagnose problems online, quote prices, promise
    response times or certify providers.
  </p>

  <h2>Why It Exists</h2>
  <p>
    When a well quits, most people search in a hurry and land on a mix of directories, ads and thin
    pages. This site tries to be the more useful landing spot: honest explanations of what a symptom
    can and cannot tell you, a form that captures what a provider actually needs to know, and clear
    disclosure about how the referral works at every step. The
    <a href="/how-referrals-work/">how referrals work page</a> details the process, and the
    <a href="/referral-disclosure/">referral disclosure</a> states the relationship plainly.
  </p>

  <h2>Accuracy Commitments</h2>
  <p>
    The site avoids manufactured trust signals. You will not find invented reviews, star ratings,
    employee photos, license claims, service guarantees or "serving since" dates here — if a claim
    appears on this site, it is either verifiable or clearly framed as general information. Where
    regulated work is discussed, the site points to the
    <a href="/licensing-information/">Tennessee licensing information page</a> instead of making assurances
    on a provider's behalf.
  </p>
</ServicePage>
